a mechanical phenomenon of nature. In another essay he contends that all versions of quantum mechanics that are compatible with the special theory of relativity make it impossible, even in principle, to present the entirety of what can be said about the world as a narrative sequence of “befores” and “afters.” Any sensible and realistic way of solving the quantum-mechanical measurement problem, Albert claims in yet another essay, is ultimately going to force us to think of particles and fields, and even the very space of the standard scientific conception of the world, as approximate and emergent. Novel discussions of the problem of deriving principled limits on what can be known, measured, or communicated from our fundamental physical theories, along with a sweeping critique of the main attempts at making sense of probabilities in many-worlds interpretations of quantum mechanics, round out the collection.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aSCIENCE / Physics / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Physics, Chemistry,  Materials Sc, Geosc 2015z9783110438789oZDB-23-DPC08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066590140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067473550740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674735507423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674735507.jpg  a978-3-11-066590-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MTPY  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MTPY  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb201